Step 1: User Request
A user on the internet enters your web app’s domain (e.g., www.myapp.com).

The DNS resolves to the public IP or Elastic IP of your EC2 instance in the public subnet.

Step 2: Internet Gateway (IGW)
The request passes through the Internet Gateway, which connects the AWS VPC to the public internet.

The route table in the public subnet directs traffic (0.0.0.0/0 → IGW) to the web server.

Step 3: Public Subnet (Web Tier)
The EC2 instance in the public subnet receives the request.

It hosts the web application (e.g., Apache, Nginx).

The instance has both:

Public IP (for external access)

Private IP (for internal communication within the VPC)

Step 4: NAT Gateway (Outbound Traffic)
If the web server or app server needs to fetch updates or connect to external APIs, it uses the NAT Gateway.

The NAT Gateway resides in the public subnet and translates private IPs to the public IP for outbound traffic.

This ensures private instances remain secure and hidden from direct internet exposure.

Step 5: Private Subnet (Application & Database Tier)
The web server forwards requests to the application server or database in the private subnet.

Communication happens via private IPs only — no public exposure.

Example:

App Server: 10.0.2.10

RDS Database: 10.0.2.30

Step 6: Response Flow
The database processes the query and sends results back to the app server.

The app server sends the processed data to the web server.

The web server responds to the user through the Internet Gateway, completing the round trip.

Step 7: Security Layers
Security Groups: Control inbound/outbound traffic at the instance level.

Example: Allow HTTP (80), HTTPS (443), SSH (22).

Network ACLs: Add subnet-level protection.

VPC Flow Logs: Capture traffic metadata for monitoring and auditing.

Internet User → Internet Gateway → Public Subnet (Web Server)
                             ↓
                     NAT Gateway → Private Subnet (App + DB)